  "prompt": "Do astronomers' know where the center of the universe is?",
  "response": "The concept of the \"center of the universe\" is a bit misleading in modern cosmology. According to the widely accepted Big Bang theory and the understanding of the universe's expansion, the universe does not have a central point. Instead, it is expanding uniformly in all directions. \n\nWhen the Big Bang occurred approximately 13.8 billion years ago, it did not happen at a specific point in space; rather, it was an expansion of space itself. Every point in the universe can be considered as being at the center of this expansion from its own perspective. Because of this, there is no defined center to the universe as we might imagine it in a three-dimensional space.\n\nIn summary, astronomers do not pinpoint a specific center of the universe, as the concept does not align with our current understanding of cosmology.",
